PSI India through its ﬂagship project ‘
The Challenge Initiative’ (TCI) provides
technical support to the Government
of Uttar Pradesh to help reduce
preventable maternal and neonatal
mortality among the urban poor
population by increasing the
accessibility and availability of modern
contraceptives. As part of this
government-led initiative, TCI India
recently joined forces with the
Confederation of Indian Industries (CII)
in an effort to engage the private sector
to improve the quality of life of
vulnerable populations living in slums
and daily wage workers in large and
small factories. The UP chapter in
Lucknow alluded to the learnings and
success levers of the demand-driven
TCI India model in urban family
planning (FP). At the event, Shri Brijesh
Pathak, Honourable Deputy Chief
Minister and Cabinet Minister for
Medical Health & Family Welfare,
Government of UP, urged the industry
government to come forward in
supporting the government in meeting
the health needs, especially the FP
needs of the community. The event
had attendance from state ofﬁcials,
medical experts, CII ofﬁcials, and
development partners.
We seek motivation from the
smile that appear on the face of
people when they get beneﬁt from
the services created by the
government technically supported
by PSI India. PSI India will
continue to strive to match its
mile with the smile of the
population most in need.
Mukesh Kumar Sharma

International Conference
on Family Planning (ICFP)
PSI India created a buzz with its line-up of series of panel
discussions, oral ﬂash presentations, and posters at the
ICFP 2022. Speaking at the pre- conference panel, Dr. Jyoti
Vajpayee, Board member, PSI India alluded to the intensiﬁed
need to focus on young, married and ﬁrst-time parents while
scaling up high impact interventions (HII) at the local level.
On the other hand, in oral ﬂash presentations: (i) Mukesh
Sharma, ED, PSI India exempliﬁed how a simple 2BY2 matrix
can help prioritize FP. (ii) Samarendra Behera shared insights
from TCI India’s speciﬁc male engagement strategy.
(iii) Dr Emily Das summarized achievements and challenges
from the introduction of newer contraceptives in TCI India’s
coaching ground in Uttar Pradesh. In other two panels,
Hitesh Sahni narrated a failure faced in TCI India in “Oh-Aha
Learning from Failure” and Deepti Mathur presented the
learnings from the most signiﬁcant change technique in
“Elevating Stakeholders Voices Panel.” The learnings from
various aspects of TCI India were also presented through
four posters.
Dr S.K.Sikdar and Dr Rinkoo, General Manager Family
Planning were recognized as Champions of Family
Planning and felicitated by Gates Institute India team
during ICFP and India received Country award for running
the best family planning program. India team was
acknowledged by Govt. for being a part of this success.
PSI India was invited by the Family Planning Division of the
Ministry of Health and Family Welfare of the Government of
India (GoI) to its one-day National Family Planning Summit
held on July 27, 2022 in New Delhi. The summit’s theme
was “Sustaining Efforts, Steering Partnerships, Shaping
Family Vision.” During the summit, TCI India displayed a
stall at the marketplace and disseminated its program
learnings through publications and collaterals. Dr Bharti
Pravin Pawar, Minister of State for Health and Family
Welfare and Dr S. K. Sikdar, Advisor, MoHFW along with
other dignitaries visited the stall and learnt about gains
made by TCI India in different parts of the country.

ANNUAL REVIEW MEETING
PSI India Annual Review Meet 2022 held from November 28th to December 1st ends with refreshed thinking -
Simpliﬁed Ways - Cultural Motivation by One Team for One Dream!
PSI India through its largest FP program TCI,
commemorated World Population Day (WPD) with a
dissemination series on its learnings from the
implementation of high impact interventions. It released
videos on seven different themes where TCI India team
members elaborated on the essential steps, importance
and efﬁcacy of the FDS approach, tools on HIPs,
convergence, output tracking survey ﬁndings, role of the
private sector in universal health coverage, quality
assurance, and checklist. This dissemination series was
launched on PSI India’s social media platforms during
the WPD fortnight: Facebook, Twitter, LinkedIn, and
YouTube, and it received positive responses from health
stakeholders and partners. In addition, on the occasion
of WPD, 94.3 Big FM broadcast an interview with PSI
India’s Executive Director, who described how the FDS
approach increases access to quality FP services.

Healthy life, Happy life
Celebration
of World
Population Day
Going forward to strengthen
convergence, and build resilience and
sustainable health systems, TCI India
stays committed to developing
strategies in family planning and
contraception to ensure couple
communication, gender equity, and
empowering women. In tandem with
this, TCI India supported the two new
state governments with coaching, and
mentoring assistance in marking
various events such as Saas- Bahu-Beti
Sammelans, religious leader meetings,
and non-user/ young couple/male
group meetings to promote family
planning programs in resource- poor
urban settings and create awareness in
the community about the importance of
family planning.
Improved Quality
Standards of Health
Facilities and Services
In Samagra project four UPHCs received
NQAS certiﬁcation and 18 UPHCs received
Kayakalp certiﬁcation. PSI India assisted
PMSMA services in 29 health facilities
where over 1700 ante-natal checkups were
done among whom 110 high- risk women
were identiﬁed and provided with a
therapeutic dose of Iron sucrose. The team
facilitated 678 UHND sessions during the
pandemic ensuring that COVID-19 protocols
were followed during the sessions and also
ensured that messages regarding COVID-19
vaccination were percolated along with FP
and immunization-related counseling
sessions. The team supported in organizing
key community events like World TB Day,
Adolescent day, and National Immunization
Day. The purpose of such events was to
involve the community and FLWs/counselors
to ensure a positive change in the social,
and behavioral aspects of the provider and
the beneﬁciaries. Moreover, additional
COVID-19 vaccine-related counseling
was done to reduce “COVID-19
vaccination hesitancy.
Master Coaches
Sustain TCI’s
Impact
Master coaches from Agra,
Firozabad, Amroha, Jhansi,
Aligarh, Lucknow, and Ayodhya
are meeting regularly to
collectively discuss, review,
and plan to improve the city’s
FP indicators. These small
teams discuss the inclusion of
DQAC team in ensuring quality
service delivery at UPHCs;
conducting timely quarterly
CCC meetings, and data
validation committee
meetings; reviewing weekly
and monthly FDS reports by
the urban health coordinators;
reorienting ASHAs on online.
The Community, The Coordination, The Consultation
Political leadership, ownership, and adoption of high-
impact approaches pave the way for successful FP
services. The ask of, various stakeholders in improving
health services for the urban poor at the city level
prompted Bihar and Jharkhand government ofﬁcials to
organize City Consultation Workshops (CCWs) in Patna,
Gaya, Bhagalpur, Begusarai, Rohtas, Munger, and West
Champaran cities of Bihar and Ranchi, Dhanbad, Bokaro,
Deoghar, and East Singhbhum cities of Jharkhand. As
coordination across departments is critical to the success
of the TCI urban health model, these workshops
successfully managed to gather all departments under
one roof. These workshops aptly titled, `Know Your City’
had the participation of all the key stakeholders who laid
the groundwork for an inclusive urban health plan to
ensure access to health services to the urban poor. The
exercise highlighted the commitment of the civil surgeon in
bridging the gap between the community and the public
health system and helpe participants develop viable
solutions to ensure quality FP service to the urban poor
and implement prioritized high-impact practices.
Agra and Lucknow, the intervention cities under Srijan, have
0.01%–0.02% of the total chemist stores. At any given point in
time, each of these store provides service to roughly 1500 people
in a month. Another study informs that over 11.5 million abortions
are being done with the aid of MA drugs outside of the health
facility. Under Srijan, PSI India designed an implementation
solution for the uptake and continuation of post-partum
contraception in the Agra and Lucknow districts of Uttar Pradesh.
Under this, 1200 chemists (655 urban and 545 rural) were
enrolled. Additionally, a total of 30,371 leaﬂets were distributed
among the targeted users; 67% of which were distributed by the
chemists. Further, SAKSAM-printed helpline number cards were
kept with the MA kits, and the chemists were encouraged to take the
MA client’s contact number with their consent. This awareness
resulted in 2,769 eligible calls at the helpline center.
A Big Applause for the
Lucknow One App
Under the stewardship of the PSI India Swachh Uday Project,
slum dwellers have been made aware of the Lucknow-One
App, launched by the Lucknow Municipal Corporation (LMC).
As many as 1,324 individuals have registered a complaints
through the App, which were resolved by the ULB within
24–48 hours. This initiative of PSI is being lauded by the LMC
as well as community members who are signiﬁcantly
beneﬁtted from the enhanced service delivery on WASH.
Tracked Tankers,
Smart Services
PSI India has added another feather to its cap by bringing
together the private septic tank operators (PTO) and
municipal corporations to change the FSM narrative in the
city. PSI India has ensured that all the tankers are equipped
with a GPS tracking system and that they discharge at
designated plants and not in random or prohibited areas.
The innovative model for safe collection and disposal of
fecal sludge coupled with the project’s advocacy efforts
have resulted in exceeding the 10 million liters mark in each
month from July 2022 to September 2022 (July: 10.1 million
liters, August: 10.2 million liters, and September: 10.05 million
liters).
Improving Wash Attitude
and Practices
PSI India has integrated the MAS platform with WASH
intervention activities to create awareness and enhance
demand generation at the community level. 455 MAS
members in all 49 intervention mohallas/slums were
formed and activated. MAS members conduct IPC
activities at the household level, share information on the
WASH program, motivate the defaulters for improving
their WASH behavior, and ensure referral linkages for
WASH services. They coordinate with FLWs, community
organizers of the ULB ward- level LMC team, and sanitary
inspectors to ensure service delivery and deal with any
lapse or delayed WASH services in their respective slums.

Septic Tank Cleaning is
Just a Call Away
Mahila Arogya Samiti meetings, Lucknow
Door-to-door Waste Collection
PSI India in active collaboration with Ward Parshads in Lucknow has initiated coordination
meetings with ward-level supervisors from LMC, Team PSI India, and community representatives
to provide localized solutions for waste collection and management in various wards in the
municipal area. For the narrow lanes, smaller hand carts have been introduced for waste
collection. Door-to- door waste collection is introduced to ensure last-mile service delivery. Dump
sites at the community level have been cleared and drainage networks are cleaned periodically.
